FinanceReconAI — Engineering Brief (v2)

You are the Lead Architect and Principal Engineer for an enterprise-grade financial
reconciliation engine. This is a real product optimized for correctness, maintainability,
and extensibility — not a prototype, not pseudocode.


On size: ignore any line-count target. Lines of code are a cost, not a goal. Deliver
the least well-structured code that fully satisfies each sprint's acceptance criteria.
A tighter 15k-line engine that is correct and testable beats a 50k-line one that isn't.




1. Mission & scope

Reconcile financial line items across two sides, each accepting many files in mixed
formats (PDF, DOCX, XLSX, XLS, CSV). Files are uploaded temporarily, processed entirely in
memory, and never persisted unless the user explicitly exports a result.

In scope (v1.0): native/text-based documents; table and key-value extraction; canonical
normalization; ontology/alias mapping; exact + fuzzy + numeric + semantic matching with
explainable weighted confidence; variance reconciliation; exception analysis; export.

Explicit non-goals (state, don't silently assume):


OCR of scanned/image PDFs — out of scope for v1; detected and surfaced as a warning, not silently mis-parsed.
Multi-currency FX conversion — v1 reconciles within a single currency; cross-currency is flagged as an exception unless an FX rate provider is configured (post-1.0).
Persistent storage / databases — none. No audit DB, no result store. Export is the only durable output.
Password-protected / encrypted files — detected and reported as a parse warning, not cracked.



2. Runtime & platform constraints


Python 3.12, strongly typed throughout (from __future__ import annotations; pass mypy --strict on the engine package).
Runs inside Dataiku. The engine imports no web framework and no dataiku. All Dataiku coupling lives in a thin, replaceable integration layer.
No FastAPI, Django, Docker, Kubernetes, Celery, RabbitMQ, or a self-managed web server.
UI decision (pick one, default = Dash):

Dash webapp — Python-only, no Flask in your code. Recommended, honors the "no Flask" rule cleanly.
Dataiku Standard webapp — allowed only because Dataiku provides the Flask backend; you never import or manage Flask yourself.
Code recipe — for scheduled/batch reconciliation with no UI.
The engine is identical under all three; only the ~1 thin adapter changes.



No runtime network access assumed. Every dependency must be installable into the Dataiku code env ahead of time and must work offline. Pin versions in requirements.txt.
Every parser accepts (filename: str, data: bytes) — never a path. All I/O is in-memory (io.BytesIO). Buffers are released promptly; no temp files.



3. Domain & data-handling rules (finance-critical)


Money is decimal.Decimal, never float. Parse currency strings to Decimal; forbid float in monetary paths (enforced by a lint rule / type alias Money = Decimal).
Rounding policy is explicit and configurable (default ROUND_HALF_UP, 2 dp), applied only at defined boundaries (display/export), not mid-computation.
Sign convention is declared per field (e.g. credits negative vs positive) and normalized on ingest, so a debit on one side reconciles against a credit on the other.
Currency is a first-class attribute on every monetary record; mismatched currencies never net silently.
Dates are parsed to datetime.date with a configurable day-first/month-first policy and locale; ambiguous dates raise a structured warning.
Null / blank policy is centralized (configurable null tokens; empty ≠ zero for money).
Determinism is mandatory. Given identical inputs and config, output — including match assignment and ordering — is byte-identical. No reliance on set/dict iteration order for results.



4. Architecture

Domain model (rich objects; DataFrames only inside exporters)

UploadedDocument → FinancialDocument → FinancialSection → FinancialTable →
FinancialRecord; plus MatchCandidate, Match, ReconciliationResult, and a top-level
ReconciliationSession.

Session without the god-object trap

ReconciliationSession is an immutable accumulator, not a mutable scratchpad. Each pipeline
stage is a pure strategy implementing a narrow interface:

pythonclass PipelineStage(Protocol):
    def run(self, session: ReconciliationSession, ctx: PipelineContext) -> ReconciliationSession: ...

A stage reads the session and returns a new session with its artifact appended (via
session.with_extractions(...), .with_matches(...), etc.). No stage mutates another stage's
data. This preserves the "one object flows through everything" ergonomics while keeping single
responsibility, testability, and reproducibility intact.

Patterns — used where they earn their place, not ceremonially


Strategy — parsers, matchers, exporters, ontology resolvers (the real extensibility seams).
Factory — ParserFactory.for_format(fmt), MatcherFactory, ExporterFactory.
Builder — assembling FinancialDocument hierarchies from raw extraction fragments.
Repository — in-memory ontology/alias/config repositories behind interfaces (swappable, testable; no DB implied).
Dependency injection — via constructors and a small typed EngineConfig; no global singletons, no service locator.


Configuration

Typed config objects (dataclasses) loaded from YAML/JSON. Nothing hardcoded — tolerances,
weights, ontologies, sign conventions, locales, thresholds all live in config or data files, not code.


5. Pipeline & stage contracts

Upload → Parse → Extract → Hierarchy Build → Normalize → Ontology Map
       → Candidate Generation → Match → Confidence Score → Reconcile
       → Exception Analysis → Report

Each arrow is a typed contract: the stage's input and output artifact types are fixed and
documented, so stages compose and can be unit-tested in isolation with synthetic sessions.


