7. Normalization & ontology


Normalization: currency/number parsing to Decimal (handles $, thousands separators, parenthesized negatives, trailing %), date parsing, whitespace/case folding for keys, configurable null tokens.
Ontology is data, not code: a versioned YAML/JSON dictionary of canonical concepts and aliases (e.g. Revenue ≈ Sales ≈ Turnover, A/R ≈ Accounts Receivable), loaded via a Repository. Adding vocabulary is a data change, never a code change.



8. Matching

Pluggable strategies, each returning candidates with a reason:
exact key, RapidFuzz string similarity, numeric proximity, hierarchy/section context,
neighbour context, alias/ontology resolution, and semantic.


Semantic: default = TF-IDF cosine (dependency-light, offline). Optional pluggable
sentence-transformers strategy for embedding similarity, gated behind config so the heavy
dependency is never mandatory.
Weighted confidence: a transparent, configurable linear (or logistic) combination of
strategy scores → [0, 1]. Weights live in config.
Explainability is required: every Match carries the contributing strategies, their
scores, the winning reason, and a human-readable explanation. No black-box matches.
Scalability: fuzzy/semantic matching is O(n·m) — mandatory blocking/indexing (by key
prefix, ontology bucket, or an exact field) before pairwise scoring, plus greedy
best-first assignment so no record is double-matched. State target scale (e.g. 100k records/side)
and enforce blocking above a configurable threshold.



9. Reconciliation output

Per matched pair and per unmatched record:
matched | unmatched, variance (Decimal), variance_%, reason, confidence,
matching_strategy, explanation, currency, and source provenance (which file/section/row).

Tolerance model (typed config, per canonical field): absolute tolerance, relative tolerance,
and — for text — a fuzzy-equality threshold. A row reconciles only if all compared fields fall
within tolerance; otherwise it's a break with per-field variance.


10. Coding standards

Python 3.12 · mypy --strict on the engine · dataclasses · enums · structured logging · SOLID ·
DI · Strategy/Factory/Builder/Repository where they earn their place · one responsibility per
class · small functions · no hardcoding · Money = Decimal (no float in money paths) ·
no god objects · deterministic outputs · pinned dependencies.


11. Testing & quality gates (every sprint)


pytest unit tests for each new stage/strategy; golden-file tests for parsers (fixture
files → expected ExtractionResult).
Property-based tests (hypothesis) for number/date/currency parsing.
Determinism test: same input twice → identical output.
Coverage gate: engine ≥ 90% line coverage; no sprint merges below it.
Tests use in-memory (filename, bytes) fixtures — never disk paths.



12. Observability & data handling


Structured logging with levels; no account numbers, amounts, or party names in logs —
log record counts, hashes, and IDs instead. Financial payloads never leave memory except on export.
Clear/free large buffers after each stage; no lingering references to raw file bytes.
Config for log verbosity; a "safe mode" that redacts even field names.



13. Delivery model

Incremental sprints; one complete, runnable sprint per response. No placeholders, no TODO
methods, no empty implementations, no pseudocode, no skipped error handling. Assume prior sprints
exist; regenerate only new/changed files; maintain backward compatibility.

Every sprint delivers: updated folder tree · new/changed files (complete) · unit tests · usage
example · architecture delta · dependency notes · acceptance criteria met · next-sprint plan.

Right-size sprints so each is fully testable — a coherent vertical slice (e.g. "CSV + XLSX
parsers with golden tests"), not an arbitrary line quota.


